Adjectives are organized in terms of antonymy. Pairs of \u201Cdirect\u201D antonyms like wet-dry and young-old reflect the strong semantic contract of their members. Each of these polar adjectives in turn is linked to a number of \u201Csemantically similar\u201D ones: dry is linked to parched, arid, dessicated and bone-dry and wet to soggy, waterlogged, etc. Semantically similar adjectives are \u201Cindirect antonyms\u201D of the contral member of the opposite pole. Relational adjectives (\"pertainyms\") point to the nouns they are derived from (criminal-crime).\xA0", mdx("br", {
